05483nam a22009375i 9780691233239DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021051640  a97806912332397 a10.1515/97806912332392doi  a(DE-B1597)618253  a(OCoLC)1334344204  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV1568b.D864 2022 7aSOC0390002bisacsh1 aDunn, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhere Paralytics Walk and the Blind See :bStories of Sickness and Disability at the Juncture of Worlds /cMary Dunn. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Bedside Manners: Illness Narratives in the Jesuit Relations -- t2 Recovery and Redemption in the Histoire de l’Hôtel Dieu de Quebec -- t3 Hagiographic Prosthetics in the Vie de la Mère Catherine de Saint-Augustin -- t4 Divine Presence in the Actes du très dévot Frère Didace Pelletier -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn exploration of early modern accounts of sickness and disability—and what they tell us about our own approach to bodily differenceIn our age of biomedicine, society often treats sickness and disability as problems in need of solution. Phenomena of embodied difference, however, have not always been seen in terms of lack and loss. Where Paralytics Walk and the Blind See explores the case of early modern Catholic Canada under French rule and shows it to be a period rich with alternative understandings of infirmity, disease, and death. Counternarratives to our contemporary assumptions, these early modern stories invite us to creatively imagine ways of living meaningfully with embodied difference today.At the heart of Dunn’s account are a range of historical sources: Jesuit stories of illness in New France, an account of Canada’s first hospital, the hagiographic vita of Catherine de Saint-Augustin, and tales of miraculous healings wrought by a dead Franciscan friar. In an early modern world that subscribed to a Christian view of salvation, both sickness and disability held significance for more than the body, opening opportunities for virtue, charity, and even redemption. Dunn demonstrates that when these reflections collide with modern thinking, the effect is a certain kind of freedom to reimagine what sickness and disability might mean to us.Reminding us that the meanings we make of embodied difference are historically conditioned, Where Paralytics Walk and the Blind See makes a forceful case for the role of history in broadening our imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDisabilities in literature. 0aSociology of disability. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCatherine de Saint-Augustin.  aCatholicism.  aChristianity.  aHotel-Dieu.  aIndigenous.  aJesuit.  aNew France.  aQuebec.  adisability.  aearly modern.  ahospital.  aillness.  amiracles.  anarrative.  anuns.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074973140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691233239?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.de